{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: New proof of (slightly weaker) partial result (Lean).","id":"vf_1a47882cd0cb4b4f","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1095.erdos_1095.variants.log_equivalent https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1095.erdos_1095.variants.log_equivalent.","id":"vf_57559a58fc3404e5","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Hosted Lean proof: plby proof of 1095 (state partial) https://github.com/plby/lean-proofs/blob/main/src/v4.29.1/ErdosProblems/Erdos1095.lean.","id":"vf_bbd53709e71283f7","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1095: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $g(k)>k+1$ be the smallest $n$ such that all prime factors of $\\binom{n}{k}$ are $>k$. Estimate $g(k)$. Current best: In \\cite{EES74} they further conjecture that\\[\\limsup \\frac{g(k+1)}{g(k)}=\\infty\\]and\\[\\liminf \\frac{g(k+1)}{g(k)}=0.\\]The lower bound was improved by Erd\\H{o}s, Lacampagne, and Selfridge \\cite{ELS93} and Granville and Ramar\\'{e} \\cite{GrRa96}. The current record is\\[g(k) \\gg \\exp(c(\\log k)^2)\\]for some $c>0$, due to Konyagin \\cite{Ko99b}. Prize: no. OEIS: A003458. Tags: binomial coefficients, number theory.","id":"vf_cf8d1fe4bb64bf4b","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1095.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_1a47882cd0cb4b4f","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:1095","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","so